'''Lloró''' is a municipality and town in the [[Chocó Department]], [[Colombia]]. It claims the second world record for highest average annual precipitation with {{convert|12717|mm|0|abbr=on}},<ref>http://www.banrepcultural.org/blaavirtual/faunayflora/pacific1/cap10.htm</ref><ref name="Lacerda2004">{{cite book|author=Luiz Drude de Lacerda|title=Environmental Geochemistry in Tropical and Subtropical Environments|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3th0bNos0OcC&pg=PA177|date=9 February 2004|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-3-540-42540-3|pages=177–}}</ref> after [[López de Micay]], which holds the record with {{convert|12892.4|mm|0|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{Cite web |last = Burt |first = Christopher C |title = Weather Extremes : New Wettest Place on Earth Discovered? |work = Weather Underground |accessdate = 2014-05-22 |date = 2013-03-18 |url = http://www.wunderground.com/blog/weatherhistorian/comment.html?entrynum=135#commenttop |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141031053635/http://www.wunderground.com/blog/weatherhistorian/comment.html?entrynum=135#commenttop |archivedate = 2014-10-31 |df = }}</ref> The rainfall data was measured in its Agricultural Farm, managed by the University of Bogotá, between 1952 and 1989. If accurate, that would make it the wettest place in the world.<ref>[http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/oa/climate/globalextremes.html#highpre NCDC: Global Measured Extremes of Temperature and Precipitation<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The town is named for Gioró, a pre-Columbian indigenous chief.
An 1853 watercolor by [[Manuel María Paz]] portrays two men in straw hats with a female vendor at a liquor stand in Lloró.<ref>{{Cite web | last = Paz | first = Manuel María | authorlink = Manuel María Paz Delgado | title = Liquor Shop in the Village of Lloró, Province of Chocó | work = World Digital Library | accessdate = 2014-05-21 | url = http://www.wdl.org/en/item/9055 }}</ref>
